    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-10-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-10-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="588"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d588">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Marshall Mission Files, Lot 54–D270</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by General <persName type="from">Chou
                            En-lai</persName> to General <persName type="to">Marshall</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">MM 201</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-10-12">October 12,
                            1946</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear General Marshall</hi>: We have not received any report
                    as to which troops conducted the incident at Hsin-Ho. Upon reading your
                    memorandum OSE 505<note n="70" xml:id="d588fn70">
                        <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>.</note> addressed to General Chou En-lai, I
                    immediately dispatched a message to Yenan authorities, asking them to probe and
                    clarify if the Communist forces near by the town did make the acts, as you
                    asserted in the memorandum. I will let you know of the result, as soon as any
                    reply is received.</p>
                <closer>For General Chou En-lai: <lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Tung Pi-Wu</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
